{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FbjmKrVh12dVwaTf5tpMDW","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have the complete picture. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: food-dictionary.ts — New \"Common title words\" Section\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Low Priority: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe section is structurally consistent with the file and serves a clear purpose — these words need to be in the dictionary so `repairOcrWord` can fix OCR-corrupted versions of them. However, there are confirmed duplicates with existing entries, several words that contain no characters tracked in `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` and are therefore inert in this context, and a few entries that are questionably generic.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Polish duplicate entries\n\nThree words in the new section already exist in the \"Polish ingredient descriptors\" block at lines 124–125:\n\n| New entry (line) | Existing entry (line) |\n|---|---|\n| `\"pieczony\"` — wait, the new section has `\"pieczone\"`, not `\"pieczony\"` | `\"pieczony\"` at line 124 |\n| `\"smazone\"` (line 142) | `\"smazony\"` at line 125 |\n| `\"gotowane\"` (line 143) | `\"gotowany\"` at line 124 |\n\n`\"pieczone\"` vs `\"pieczony\"`, `\"smazone\"` vs `\"smazony\"`, `\"gotowane\"` vs `\"gotowany\"` are distinct grammatical forms (neuter plural vs masculine singular), so they are **not duplicates** — they are genuinely missing forms. This is actually correct. No issue here.\n\n### 2. Words with no OCR-repairable characters\n\n`repairOcrWord` only triggers when the input contains characters from `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS`: `0`, `1`, `4`, `5`, `¡`, `í`, `€`. Words that contain none of the *substitutable letters* (o, i, l, a, s, e) can never be repaired via this mechanism. However, the function checks `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` against the *input* before doing anything — it only processes words that contain those digit/artifact characters. So the dictionary lookup only fires when the corrupted form contains one of those artifacts.\n\nThe real question for each new word: **can a plausible OCR corruption of it land in a candidate that the dictionary lookup would validate?** Let's work through the high-risk ones:\n\n- `\"with\"` — no substitutable characters (w, i, t, h → `1` for `i` → `w1th`). `w1th` → candidate `with`. Valid use case.\n- `\"the\"` — `t`, `h`, `e` → `€` for `e` → `th€` → candidate `the`. Valid.\n- `\"and\"` — no substitutable letters by the current table. `a`, `n`, `d` — `4` maps to `a`, so `4nd` → `and`. Valid.\n- `\"for\"` — `f`, `o`, `r` — `0` maps to `o`, so `f0r` → `for`. Valid.\n- `\"new\"` — `n`, `e`, `w` — `€` maps to `e`, so `n€w` → `new`. Valid.\n- `\"old\"` — `o`, `l`, `d` — `0` for `o`, `1` for `l`, so `01d`/`0ld`/`o1d` → `old`. Valid.\n\nThe words all have plausible OCR corruption paths. No purely inert entries found.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"with\", \"from\", \"over\", \"under\" — false positive risk\n\nThese are the most common English words. The `repairOcrWord` function has no title-context filter: it operates word-by-word on the full text, not just on title candidates. This means any text fragment containing `f0r`, `4nd`, `th€`, etc. — even in ingredient quantities, instructions, or unrelated OCR noise — will be silently repaired to `\"for\"`, `\"and\"`, `\"the\"`.\n\nWhether this is a problem depends on downstream usage. If the repaired text feeds back into the title extractor's scoring, injecting function words into non-title lines could inflate title scores for those lines. The concern is moderate because these corrupted forms are also unlikely to appear frequently in practice.\n\n**Recommendation**: Acceptable as-is if the downstream scoring discounts function words (verify in title-extractor.ts scoring logic), but worth a comment explaining why function words are intentionally included.\n\n### 4. \"simple\", \"quick\", \"easy\" — too generic, limited OCR corruption paths\n\n- `\"simple\"` — `s`, `i`, `m`, `p`, `l`, `e` — `5` for `s`, `1` for `i`/`l`, `€` for `e` → multiple corruptions possible (`51mple`, `s1mple`, `simpl€`). Reachable.\n- `\"quick\"` — `q`, `u`, `i`, `c`, `k` — only `1` for `i` → `qu1ck`. Narrow but valid.\n- `\"easy\"` — `e`, `a`, `s`, `y` — `€` for `e`, `4` for `a`, `5` for `s` → `€asy`, `e4sy`, `ea5y`, `€45y`. Valid.\n\nThese words are common enough in recipe titles that inclusion is justified. Acceptable.\n\n### 5. Grammatical form gaps in the Polish section\n\nThe new section adds `\"pieczone\"`, `\"smazone\"`, `\"gotowane\"`, `\"duszone\"`, `\"duszony\"`, `\"domowy\"`, `\"domowe\"`, `\"tradycyjny\"`, `\"tradycyjne\"` but omits several high-frequency grammatical forms:\n\n- `\"pieczony\"` (masculine) and `\"pieczona\"` (feminine) complement `\"pieczone\"` (neuter/plural) — only `\"pieczony\"` is already in the file\n- `\"domowa\"` (feminine form of `\"domowy\"`) is absent\n- `\"tradycyjna\"` (feminine) is absent\n- `\"duszony\"` is included, but `\"duszona\"` is not\n\nThis is incomplete coverage of the stated goal (\"Polish common title words\"). Not a blocking issue, but gaps will mean some corrupted words go unrepaired.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority\n\n### 6. \"buns\", \"rolls\" — plurals alongside singulars\n\n`\"bun\"` and `\"buns\"`, `\"roll\"` and `\"rolls\"` are both included. This is consistent with the rest of the file which generally uses only singular/root forms (e.g. `\"cookie\"` not `\"cookies\"`, `\"noodle\"` not `\"noodles\"`). The plurals are harmless but inconsistent with the file's convention.\n\nThe only reason to include both forms would be if the corrupted input is always the full word — since OCR typically preserves word boundaries, `r0lls` → `rolls` and `r0ll` → `roll` are distinct repair targets. If both are real OCR inputs you've seen, keep both; otherwise drop the plurals for consistency.\n\n### 7. Section name vs file-level purpose mismatch\n\nThe file header comment at line 2 says \"~500 common English and Polish food/cooking words\". The new section is titled \"Common title words (for OCR repair)\" — but all words in the file are \"for OCR repair\". The section title accurately names *what's new* about these words (they're title structural words, not food terms), so the heading is useful. Consider updating the file-level comment to acknowledge this broader scope, e.g. \"food/cooking words and common recipe title words\".\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The section is correctly placed before the closing `]);` and uses the same comment style (line divider + inline sub-comments) as every other section.\n- The \"(without diacritics)\" convention is followed correctly for Polish entries.\n- Limiting new adjectives to those genuinely common in recipe titles (`\"classic\"`, `\"quick\"`, `\"easy\"`, `\"light\"`) rather than adding general English adjectives is the right call.\n- Grouping by semantic role within the section (prepositions, adjectives, short food terms, Polish) mirrors the structure used in the rest of the file.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Actionable Items\n\n| Priority | Item |\n|---|---|\n| MEDIUM | Add a comment explaining why function words (`\"the\"`, `\"and\"`, etc.) are intentionally included, acknowledging false-positive trade-off |\n| MEDIUM | Consider adding missing Polish feminine forms (`\"domowa\"`, `\"tradycyjna\"`, `\"pieczona\"`, `\"duszona\"`) if the goal is systematic coverage |\n| LOW | Decide whether `\"buns\"` and `\"rolls\"` are needed alongside `\"bun\"` and `\"roll\"` given the file's singular-form convention |\n| LOW | Update the file-level comment on line 2 to reflect that the dictionary now includes structural title words, not only food terms |\n\nNo blocking issues. The change is safe to merge with the medium-priority items tracked as follow-up."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ab4acfc054e0afc32 (for resuming to co